SIMPLE: identity
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Identity
<hw>I*den"ti*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Identities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F.
<ets>identit⟦eacute⟧</ets>, LL. <ets>identitas</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>idem</ets> the same, from the root of <ets>is</ets> he, that; cf.
Skr. <ets>idam</ets> this. Cf. <er>Item</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The state or quality of being identical, or the same;
sameness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Identity</qex> is a relation between our cognitions of a
thing, not between things themselves.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The condition of being the same with something
described or asserted, or of possessing a character claimed; <as>as, to
establish the <ex>identity</ex> of stolen goods</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>An identical equation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ideo-</ent>⟦br⟧
